    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey so i was reading about space stuff and i dont really get what a planetary conjunction actually is. like do they actually hit each other or im just seeing them close together from earth? also how does orbital inclination play into how close they look?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A planetary conjunction occurs when multiple planets appear close together in the sky at the same time, but they aren't actually colliding. This happens when the observer's view of each planet is temporarily aligned with the Earth, revealing them in close proximity to one another. The planets' actual distances from each other remain unchanged, and their paths just happen to intersect from Earth. Orbital inclination, which is the angle at which a planet orbits the sky, can affect how close they appear to each other from our vantage point.",
