      "content": "A higher orbital inclination can make a significant difference in how close the planets appear to be during conjunction. For example, when the inclination is high, such as with some dwarf planets, they may appear as a small, close pair, even if they're actually quite far apart. Conversely, a low inclination, like near the plane of the solar system, may make it difficult or even impossible for them to appear together in a single image.",
